{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015EULtmmqRbVET5ZrMjKn4P","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Wckf6yck73uEuUxVfTFma9","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"theorem_title":"Pinsker's inequality via reduction to the Bernoulli case","theorem_statement":"Let \((X,\mathcal{F})\) be a measurable space and let \(P,Q\) be probability measures on \((X,\mathcal{F})\) with \(P\ll Q\). Then \(D_{\mathrm{KL}}(P\|Q)\ge 2\,\|P-Q\|_{\mathrm{TV}}^2\), where \(\|P-Q\|_{\mathrm{TV}}:=\sup_{A\in\mathcal{F}}|P(A)-Q(A)|\) and \(D_{\mathrm{KL}}(P\|Q):=\int_X\log\!\left(\tfrac{dP}{dQ}\right)\,dP\).","root_node_id":"root","nodes":"[
  {
    "id": "root",
    "title": "Pinsker's inequality",
    "display_label": "Pinsker's inequality: \(D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P\\|Q)\\ge 2\\,\\|P-Q\\|_{\\mathrm{TV}}^2\)",
    "informal_statement": "Let \(P,Q\) be probability measures on \((X,\\mathcal{F})\) with \(P\\ll Q\). Then \(D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P\\|Q)\\ge 2\\,\\|P-Q\\|_{\\mathrm{TV}}^2\).",
    "informal_proof_text": "Set \(\\delta:=\\|P-Q\\|_{\\mathrm{TV}}\). By the Hahn decomposition, choose \(A\\in\\mathcal{F}\) with \(P(A)-Q(A)=\\delta\\ge 0\). Set \(p:=P(A)\), \(q:=Q(A)\), and define \(T:=\\mathbf{1}_A:X\\to\\{0,1\\}\). The pushforward measures satisfy \(T_\\#P=(p,1-p)\) and \(T_\\#Q=(q,1-q)\), so\n\\[D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(T_\\#P\\|T_\\#Q)=p\\log\\!\\left(\\frac pq\\right)+(1-p)\\log\\!\\left(\\frac{1-p}{1-q}\\right).\\]\nBy the data-processing inequality (DPI), \(D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P\\|Q)\\ge D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(T_\\#P\\|T_\\#Q)\\). By the Bernoulli scalar inequality, \(D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(T_\\#P\\|T_\\#Q)\\ge 2(p-q)^2=2\\delta^2\\). Chaining the two inequalities gives \(D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P\\|Q)\\ge 2\\delta^2=2\\,\\|P-Q\\|_{\\mathrm{TV}}^2\\)."
  },
  {
    "id": "dpi",
    "title": "Data-processing inequality for KL divergence",
    "display_label": "DPI: \(D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P\\|Q)\\ge D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(T_\\#P\\|T_\\#Q)\)",
    "informal_statement": "Let \(P,Q\) be probability measures on \((X,\\mathcal{F})\) with \(P\\ll Q\), and let \(T:(X,\\mathcal{F})\\to(Y,\\mathcal{G})\) be measurable. Then \(D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P\\|Q)\\ge D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(T_\\#P\\|T_\\#Q)\).",
    "informal_proof_text": "This is the standard data-processing (information monotonicity) inequality for relative entropy. One proof proceeds by the log-sum inequality / Jensen: writing the pushforward densities as conditional expectations, the joint relative entropy dominates the marginal one. Formally, by the chain rule for KL divergence and nonnegativity of conditional KL, \(D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P\\|Q)=D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(T_\\#P\\|T_\\#Q)+\\mathbb{E}_{T_\\#P}[D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P(\\cdot\\mid T)\\|Q(\\cdot\\mid T))]\\ge D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(T_\\#P\\|T_\\#Q)\\). Applied here with \(T=\\mathbf{1}_A\\), the coarsened binary observation forgets information, so relative entropy cannot increase."
  },
  {
    "id": "bernoulli_ineq",
    "title": "Bernoulli scalar inequality",
    "display_label": "Bernoulli inequality: \(p\\log\\frac{p}{q}+(1-p)\\log\\frac{1-p}{1-q}\\ge 2(p-q)^2\)",
    "informal_statement": "For all \(p,q\\in(0,1)\),\n\\[p\\log\\!\\left(\\frac{p}{q}\\right)+(1-p)\\log\\!\\left(\\frac{1-p}{1-q}\\right)\\ge 2(p-q)^2.\\]",
    "informal_proof_text": "Fix \(q\\in(0,1)\) and define\n\\[F_q(p):=p\\log\\!\\left(\\frac pq\\right)+(1-p)\\log\\!\\left(\\frac{1-p}{1-q}\\right)-2(p-q)^2,\\quad p\\in(0,1).\\]\nWe show \(F_q(p)\\ge 0\\) for all \(p\\in(0,1)\\).\n\n**Value at \(p=q\):** \(F_q(q)=0\\cdot\\log 1+0\\cdot\\log 1-0=0\\).\n\n**First derivative:**\n\\[F_q'(p)=\\log\\!\\left(\\frac{p}{q}\\right)-\\log\\!\\left(\\frac{1-p}{1-q}\\right)-4(p-q)=\\log\\!\\left(\\frac{p(1-q)}{q(1-p)}\\right)-4(p-q).\\]\nAt \(p=q\\): \(F_q'(q)=\\log 1-0=0\\).\n\n**Second derivative:**\n\\[F_q''(p)=\\frac{1}{p}+\\frac{1}{1-p}-4=\\frac{1}{p(1-p)}-4.\\]\nSince \(p(1-p)\\le\\tfrac14\\) for all \(p\\in(0,1)\\) (AM–GM), we have \(\\tfrac{1}{p(1-p)}\\ge 4\\), so \(F_q''(p)\\ge 0\\).\n\n**Conclusion:** \(F_q\\) is convex on \((0,1)\\), and \(p=q\\) is a critical point with \(F_q(q)=0\\). A critical point of a convex function is a global minimizer, so \(F_q(p)\\ge F_q(q)=0\\) for all \(p\\in(0,1)\\)."
  }
